---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const people = await getCollection('people');
const docs = await getCollection('documents');
const arts = await getCollection('artifacts');
const places = await getCollection('places');
---
<BaseLayout title="Eesley · Wildermuth" description="A narrative archive of the Eesley and Wildermuth families.">
  <section class="prose max-w-prose">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif mb-2">Eesley · Wildermuth</h1>
    <p class="text-ink/70 italic mt-0">
      A narrative archive of two American families &mdash; one out of Stratford-on-Avon
      by way of a Scottish flour mill, one out of Württemberg by way of Marietta &mdash;
      meeting in a single generation.
    </p>

    <p>
      This site was inspired by the work of <strong>Robert Earl Wildermuth</strong>, Chuck's maternal
      grandfather, who in his retirement turned to genealogy and wrote the memoirs, the
      combat log, the &ldquo;Return to Germany&rdquo; travelogue, and the German-ancestor sketches
      that frame everything maternal here. He closed his last manuscript by addressing
      <em>&ldquo;future genealogists.&rdquo;</em> This site is one of them answering.
    </p>

    <p>
      Three keepers built the paternal side. <strong>Mary Eesley Bean</strong>'s 1985 indented register laid
      down the relationships from Stratford through to Marietta. <strong>Margaret &ldquo;Maggie&rdquo; Eesley</strong>'s
      four-generation photo archive carries the faces. <strong>Aunt Jeanne (Eesley) Kamiab</strong>
      contributed many of the photographs and the oral history this site relies on &mdash;
      including the wartime account of how Stella Sunn came to live with the Eesleys.
    </p>

    <p>
      A fourth keeper, still at work, is <strong>Dale Eesley</strong>, whose careful and thorough
      genealogical work on <a href="https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/GMLW-PXW">FamilySearch</a>
      is the most current and best-sourced single account of the line. Chuck collaborates
      with Dale on the same FamilySearch tree; a parallel Ancestry.com version of the tree
      exists as well, but Dale and Chuck treat the FamilySearch one as canonical. The
      <a href="/docs/dale-eesley-familysearch-tree/">structured tree as a downloadable GEDCOM</a>
      &mdash; 3,428 individuals across 1,510 families &mdash; is here too. It is the source future
      Eesley genealogists should consult first.
    </p>

    <p>
      Their work is the archive; this site is the next layer of it.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The Zhou side &mdash; live and growing.</strong> The Eesley and Wildermuth lines
      have a year of intensive work behind them; the <strong>Zhou family of Qingdao, Shandong</strong> &mdash;
      <a href="/family/lijie-zhou/">Lijie</a>'s line &mdash; is now navigable in its own
      <a href="/zh/" lang="zh">中文 hub</a>, built out four generations deep, and being extended
      branch by branch. Name characters and earlier generations are still being confirmed with the family.
    </p>

    <hr class="my-8 border-rule" />

    <h2 class="text-2xl mt-8">Enter</h2>
    <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 mt-4">
      <li><a href="/family/">The family</a> &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; <span class="text-ink/60 text-sm">{people.length} people</span></li>
      <li><a href="/docs/">Stories &amp; memoirs</a> &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; <span class="text-ink/60 text-sm">{docs.length} documents</span></li>
      <li><a href="/places/">Places, then &amp; now</a> &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; <span class="text-ink/60 text-sm">{places.length} sites &mdash; including the German villages, photographed across generations</span></li>
      <li><a href="/archive/">Photo &amp; letter archive</a> &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; <span class="text-ink/60 text-sm">{arts.length} artifacts</span></li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
